<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-578  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 578.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  August 1990 v15 n8 p227(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Managing multimedia: authoring systems are the glue that holdsmultimedia applications together.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Veljkov, Mark D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Criteria for selecting an authoring system are divided into toolsthat ease development of multimedia applications and capabilitiesthat can be included in the applications.andP;  Authoring systems usenatural language rather than programming language to createinteractive multimedia education and training programs.andP;  Thesystems are available for common computer platforms.andP;  Desirableauthoring system programming features include ease of learning anduse, no need for programmer support or procedural programming,acceptance of external text and graphics input, ability to createinput files, control of external media, courseware user trackingand evaluation, and run-time option.andP;  The system should be able tocreate courseware that is easy to move around in, supportshypertext functions, has context-sensitive help and interactivegraphics, and fully integrates sound, animation, graphics, textand video.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Authoring LanguagesSystem DesignCriteriaSoftware SelectionRequirements AnalysisApplications ProgrammingMultimedia Software.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>